At pH = 7.00, the alkalinity is due to the \([HCO_3^-]\) and hence \([HCO_3^-] = 2.00 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{eq/L}\). The \([OH^-] = 1.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{eq/L}\) and the \([CO_2]\) can be calculated by substituting the values of \([HCO_3^-]\) and \([H^+]\) in the \(K_{a1}\) expression and then solving for \([CO_2]\). The \([CO_3^{2-}]\) can be calculated by substituting the values of \([HCO_3^-]\) and \([H^+]\) in the \(K_{a2}\) expression:
\[
K_{a1} = 4.45 \times 10^{-7} = \frac{\left[1.00 \times 10^{-7}\right] \times \left[2.00 \times 10^{-3}\right]}{\left[{\rm CO}_2\right]}
\]
\[
[CO_2] = 4.49 \times 10^{-4}
\]
\[
K_{a2} = 4.69 \times 10^{-11} = \frac{\left[1.00 \times 10^{-7}\right] \times \left[{\rm CO}_3^{2-}\right]}{\left[2.00 \times 10^{-3}\right]}
\]
\[
[CO_3^{2-}] = 9.38 \times 10^{-7}
\]
